00:12:49,769 --> 00:12:53,788
<font color="#FFFFFF">Just having an Enigma machine
doesn't help you to decode the messages.</font>

195
00:12:54,524 --> 00:12:56,342
<font color="#FFFFFF">Very good, Mr. Turing.</font>

196
00:12:56,442 --> 00:12:59,961
<font color="#FFFFFF">To decode a message, you need
to know the machine's settings.</font>

197
00:13:00,279 --> 00:13:04,642
<font color="#FFFFFF">Now, the Germans switch settings
every day, promptly at midnight.</font>

198
00:13:04,741 --> 00:13:08,302
<font color="#FFFFFF">We usually intercept our first message
around 6:00am.</font>

199
00:13:08,788 --> 00:13:13,610
<font color="#FFFFFF">Which gives you exactly
18 hours every day to crack the code</font>

200
00:13:13,710 --> 00:13:16,144
<font color="#FFFFFF">before it changes and
you start again.</font>

201
00:13:16,629 --> 00:13:19,815
<font color="#FFFFFF">Five rotors. 10
plugboard cables.</font>

202
00:13:20,383 --> 00:13:22,118
<font color="#FFFFFF">- That's one million...
- 1,000 million.</font>

203
00:13:22,217 --> 00:13:23,827
<font color="#FFFFFF">- No, it's... I've got it.
- It's a million million.</font>

204
00:13:23,927 --> 00:13:25,447
<font color="#FFFFFF">Well, it's in the millions, obviously.</font>

205
00:13:25,471 --> 00:13:28,573
<font color="#FFFFFF">There's over 150 million million million
possible settings.</font>

206
00:13:28,765 --> 00:13:30,325
<font color="#FFFFFF">Very good.</font>

207
00:13:30,476 --> 00:13:33,879
<font color="#FFFFFF">One hundred and fifty-nine,
if you want to be exact about it,</font>

208
00:13:33,980 --> 00:13:37,331
<font color="#FFFFFF">1-5-9 with 18 zeros behind it.</font>

209
00:13:37,567 --> 00:13:39,000
<font color="#FFFFFF">Possibilities.</font>

210
00:13:39,652 --> 00:13:40,886
<font color="#FFFFFF">Every single day.</font>

211
00:13:40,986 --> 00:13:43,547
<font color="#FFFFFF">Gentlemen, meet Hugh Alexander.</font>

212
00:13:43,907 --> 00:13:46,809
<font color="#FFFFFF">I personally selected him
to run this unit.</font>

213
00:13:46,909 --> 00:13:47,976
<font color="#FFFFFF">Didn't you...</font>

214
00:13:48,076 --> 00:13:50,278
<font color="#FFFFFF">Mr. Alexander won Britain's
national chess championship.</font>

215
00:13:51,080 --> 00:13:52,981
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Twice.
- You're not the only one</font>

216
00:13:53,081 --> 00:13:55,818
<font color="#FFFFFF">who's good at games
round here, Turing.</font>

217
00:13:55,918 --> 00:13:59,322
<font color="#FFFFFF">Are we to work together, then?
I prefer to have my own office.</font>

218
00:13:59,422 --> 00:14:00,942
<font color="#FFFFFF">You're a team and you
will work as one.</font>

219
00:14:01,006 --> 00:14:04,159
<font color="#FFFFFF">I don't have time to explain myself
as I go along</font>

220
00:14:04,259 --> 00:14:06,861
<font color="#FFFFFF">and I'm afraid these men
would only slow me down.</font>

221
00:14:07,764 --> 00:14:08,998
<font color="#FFFFFF">If you can't play together,</font>

222
00:14:09,097 --> 00:14:11,208
<font color="#FFFFFF">then I'm afraid
we can't let you play at all.</font>

223
00:14:11,308 --> 00:14:13,211
<font color="#FFFFFF">This is Stewart Menzies. MI6.</font>

224
00:14:13,311 --> 00:14:15,879
<font color="#FFFFFF">There are only five divisions
of Military Intelligence.</font>

225
00:14:15,980 --> 00:14:18,674
<font color="#FFFFFF">- There is no MI6.
- Exactly.</font>

226
00:14:18,774 --> 00:14:20,375
<font color="#FFFFFF">That's the spirit.</font>

227
00:14:21,693 --> 00:14:24,264
<font color="#FFFFFF">Mr. Turing, do you know
how many British servicemen have died</font>

228
00:14:24,364 --> 00:14:25,713
<font color="#FFFFFF">because of Enigma?</font>

229
00:14:26,032 --> 00:14:28,133
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Uh, no, I don't.
- Three.</font>

230
00:14:29,284 --> 00:14:31,385
<font color="#FFFFFF">While we've been having
this conversation.</font>

231
00:14:33,539 --> 00:14:35,139
<font color="#FFFFFF">Oh, look, there's another.</font>

232
00:14:36,209 --> 00:14:38,100
<font color="#FFFFFF">I rather hope he
didn't have a family.</font>

233
00:14:39,003 --> 00:14:41,480
<font color="#FFFFFF">This war Commander Denniston's
been going on about,</font>

234
00:14:42,130 --> 00:14:43,606
<font color="#FFFFFF">we're not winning it.</font>

235
00:14:44,133 --> 00:14:46,567
<font color="#FFFFFF">Break the code,
at least we have a chance.</font>

236
00:14:49,806 --> 00:14:52,709
<font color="#FFFFFF">Shall we leave the children alone
with their new toy?</font>

237
00:14:58,022 --> 00:14:59,581
<font color="#FFFFFF">All right, gentlemen...</font>

238
00:15:03,027 --> 00:15:04,503
<font color="#FFFFFF">let's play.</font>

239
00:15:07,532 --> 00:15:10,258
<font color="#FFFFFF">The game was quite a simple one.</font>

240
00:15:12,787 --> 00:15:14,898
<font color="#FFFFFF">Every single German message,</font>

241
00:15:14,998 --> 00:15:17,817
<font color="#FFFFFF">every surprise attack,
every bombing run,</font>

242
00:15:17,917 --> 00:15:18,942
<font color="#FFFFFF">every, uh...</font>

243
00:15:19,043 --> 00:15:21,436
<font color="#FFFFFF">imminent U-boat assault.</font>

244
00:15:26,341 --> 00:15:28,652
<font color="#FFFFFF">They were all floating through the air.</font>

245
00:15:38,520 --> 00:15:39,995
<font color="#FFFFFF">Radio signals that,</font>

246
00:15:41,190 --> 00:15:44,927
<font color="#FFFFFF">well, any schoolboy
with an AM kit could intercept.</font>

247
00:15:48,280 --> 00:15:50,716
<font color="#FFFFFF">The trick was that
they were encrypted.</font>

248
00:16:00,543 --> 00:16:03,904
<font color="#FFFFFF">One hundred and fifty-nine
million million million</font>

249
00:16:04,004 --> 00:16:05,938
<font color="#FFFFFF">possible Enigma settings.</font>

250
00:16:07,174 --> 00:16:09,609
<font color="#FFFFFF">All we had to do
was try each one.</font>

251
00:16:12,721 --> 00:16:15,457
<font color="#FFFFFF">But if we had 10 men
checking one setting a minute</font>

252
00:16:15,557 --> 00:16:19,995
<font color="#FFFFFF">for 24 hours every day
and seven days every week,</font>

253
00:16:21,355 --> 00:16:26,500
<font color="#FFFFFF">how many days do you think it would take
to check each of the settings?</font>

254
00:16:29,279 --> 00:16:32,006
<font color="#FFFFFF">It's not days, it's years.</font>

255
00:16:33,743 --> 00:16:36,845
<font color="#FFFFFF">It's 20 million years.</font>

256
00:16:38,246 --> 00:16:39,649
<font color="#FFFFFF">To stop a coming attack,</font>

257
00:16:39,749 --> 00:16:44,186
<font color="#FFFFFF">we would have to check
20 million years' worth of settings</font>

258
00:16:44,961 --> 00:16:46,687
<font color="#FFFFFF">in 20 minutes.</font>

259
00:17:13,990 --> 00:17:16,134
<font color="#FFFFFF">I'm famished. Lunch?</font>

260
00:17:17,494 --> 00:17:20,387
<font color="#FFFFFF">Good Lord, what is it about women
with little hats?</font>

261
00:17:27,547 --> 00:17:30,606
<font color="#FFFFFF">The boys...
We're going to get some lunch.</font>

262
00:17:34,804 --> 00:17:36,330
<font color="#FFFFFF">Alan?</font>

263
00:17:36,431 --> 00:17:38,990
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Yes?
- I said we're going to get some lunch.</font>

264
00:17:42,729 --> 00:17:44,453
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Alan?
- Yes?</font>

265
00:17:44,646 --> 00:17:46,957
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Can you hear me?
- Yes.</font>

266
00:17:47,650 --> 00:17:49,416
<font color="#FFFFFF">I said we're off to get some...</font>

267
00:17:49,736 --> 00:17:51,471
<font color="#FFFFFF">This is starting to get
a little bit repetitive.</font>

268
00:17:51,570 --> 00:17:52,638
<font color="#FFFFFF">What is?</font>

269
00:17:52,739 --> 00:17:54,557
<font color="#FFFFFF">I had asked if you wanted
to come to lunch with us.</font>

270
00:17:54,656 --> 00:17:56,224
<font color="#FFFFFF">Er, no, you didn't.</font>

271
00:17:56,325 --> 00:17:58,509
<font color="#FFFFFF">You said you were going
to get some lunch.</font>

272
00:17:59,077 --> 00:18:00,563
<font color="#FFFFFF">Have I offended you in some way?</font>

273
00:18:00,663 --> 00:18:02,137
<font color="#FFFFFF">Why would you think that?</font>

274
00:18:02,914 --> 00:18:04,476
<font color="#FFFFFF">Would you like to come
to lunch with us?</font>

275
00:18:04,500 --> 00:18:05,567
<font color="#FFFFFF">What time's lunchtime?</font>

276
00:18:05,667 --> 00:18:08,603
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Christ, Alan, it's a bleeding sandwich.
- What is?</font>

277
00:18:09,087 --> 00:18:11,615
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Lunch.
- I don't like sandwiches.</font>

278
00:18:11,715 --> 00:18:13,275
<font color="#FFFFFF">Never mind.</font>

279
00:18:14,009 --> 00:18:17,788
<font color="#FFFFFF">You know, to pull off
this irascible genius routine,</font>

280
00:18:17,888 --> 00:18:19,749
<font color="#FFFFFF">one actually has to
be a genius, Alan.</font>

281
00:18:19,848 --> 00:18:22,250
<font color="#FFFFFF">And yet we're the ones
making progress here, aren't we?</font>

282
00:18:22,351 --> 00:18:23,795
<font color="#FFFFFF">You are?</font>

283
00:18:23,894 --> 00:18:25,452
<font color="#FFFFFF">Yes, we are.</font>

284
00:18:26,355 --> 00:18:29,299
<font color="#FFFFFF">We have decrypted a number
of German messages</font>

285
00:18:29,400 --> 00:18:32,001
<font color="#FFFFFF">by analysing the frequency
of letter distribution.</font>

286
00:18:33,028 --> 00:18:35,013
<font color="#FFFFFF">Oh, even a broken clock is right
twice a day.</font>

287
00:18:35,114 --> 00:18:37,349
<font color="#FFFFFF">That's not progress.
That's just blind luck.</font>

288
00:18:37,450 --> 00:18:41,469
<font color="#FFFFFF">I'm designing a machine that will
allow us to break every message,</font>

289
00:18:41,746 --> 00:18:44,346
<font color="#FFFFFF">every day, instantly.</font>

290
00:18:46,459 --> 00:18:47,976
<font color="#FFFFFF">Who's hungry?</font>

291
00:18:48,795 --> 00:18:51,145
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Let's go.
- I'm hungry.</font>

292
00:18:53,382 --> 00:18:56,118
<font color="#FFFFFF">- What?
- Peter asked who was hungry.</font>

293
00:18:56,219 --> 00:18:57,693
<font color="#FFFFFF">Can I have some soup, please?</font>

294
00:20:25,182 --> 00:20:27,116
<font color="#FFFFFF">What do you mean, classified?</font>

295
00:20:28,019 --> 00:20:30,587
<font color="#FFFFFF">No, I am aware of the literal meaning
of the word "classified",</font>

296
00:20:30,688 --> 00:20:32,298
<font color="#FFFFFF">what I'm asking is
why would a maths professor</font>

297
00:20:32,397 --> 00:20:34,582
<font color="#FFFFFF">have his military
records classified?</font>

298
00:20:36,652 --> 00:20:38,627
<font color="#FFFFFF">Yeah, well, I will come down.</font>

299
00:20:59,342 --> 00:21:01,786
<font color="#FFFFFF">Pardon me, I'd like to see
some documents, if I may.</font>

300
00:21:01,885 --> 00:21:05,404
<font color="#FFFFFF">Service records of a
Mr... Turing, Alan.</font>

301
00:21:06,848 --> 00:21:08,324
<font color="#FFFFFF">Foreign Office sent me.</font>

302
00:21:14,522 --> 00:21:16,290
<font color="#FFFFFF">This is unacceptable.</font>

303
00:21:17,108 --> 00:21:18,803
<font color="#FFFFFF">If you wish to discuss a complaint,</font>

304
00:21:18,903 --> 00:21:20,304
<font color="#FFFFFF">I suggest you make a
proper appointment.</font>

305
00:21:20,403 --> 00:21:22,130
<font color="#FFFFFF">Alexander... Complaint?</font>

306
00:21:22,698 --> 00:21:27,103
<font color="#FFFFFF">No. No, Hugh Alexander has denied
my requisition for parts and equipment</font>

307
00:21:27,202 --> 00:21:28,604
<font color="#FFFFFF">that I need to build the machine
I have designed.</font>

308
00:21:28,703 --> 00:21:31,106
<font color="#FFFFFF">Your fellow code-breakers
are refusing to work with you</font>

309
00:21:31,207 --> 00:21:32,817
<font color="#FFFFFF">and they've filed a
formal complaint.</font>

310
00:21:32,916 --> 00:21:34,676
<font color="#FFFFFF">It is inspired
by an old Polish code machine,</font>

311
00:21:34,710 --> 00:21:37,320
<font color="#FFFFFF">only this one is
infinitely more advanced.</font>

312
00:21:37,421 --> 00:21:38,901
<font color="#FFFFFF">If you don't respond
to the complaint,</font>

313
00:21:38,964 --> 00:21:40,845
<font color="#FFFFFF">I shall have to take it up
with the Home Office.</font>

314
00:21:40,883 --> 00:21:42,285
<font color="#FFFFFF">Put those files by my desk.</font>

315
00:21:42,384 --> 00:21:43,827
<font color="#FFFFFF">Fine. My response is
they're all idiots,</font>

316
00:21:43,927 --> 00:21:45,954
<font color="#FFFFFF">fire them and use the savings
to fund my machine.</font>

317
00:21:46,055 --> 00:21:48,530
<font color="#FFFFFF">I only need about £100,000.</font>

318
00:21:49,976 --> 00:21:51,326
<font color="#FFFFFF">£100,000?</font>

319
00:21:52,979 --> 00:21:54,703
<font color="#FFFFFF">Why are you building a machine?</font>

320
00:21:55,230 --> 00:21:57,967
<font color="#FFFFFF">It's highly technical,
you wouldn't understand.</font>

321
00:21:58,067 --> 00:22:00,375
<font color="#FFFFFF">I suggest you make
the effort to try.</font>

322
00:22:02,238 --> 00:22:05,974
<font color="#FFFFFF">Enigma is an extremely
well-designed machine.</font>

323
00:22:06,075 --> 00:22:09,144
<font color="#FFFFFF">Our problem is that
we're only using men to try to beat it.</font>

324
00:22:09,244 --> 00:22:12,846
<font color="#FFFFFF">What if only a machine
can defeat another machine?</font>

325
00:22:13,582 --> 00:22:15,099
<font color="#FFFFFF">Well, that's not very technical.</font>

326
00:22:15,584 --> 00:22:17,528
<font color="#FFFFFF">Hugh Alexander
is in charge of your unit.</font>

327
00:22:17,627 --> 00:22:19,186
<font color="#FFFFFF">He said no and that is that.</font>

328
00:22:19,462 --> 00:22:21,064
<font color="#FFFFFF">I simply don't have time for this.</font>

329
00:22:21,589 --> 00:22:23,775
<font color="#FFFFFF">Have you ever won a war, Turing?</font>

330
00:22:24,926 --> 00:22:27,194
<font color="#FFFFFF">I have. Do you know
how it's done?</font>

331
00:22:27,680 --> 00:22:30,280
<font color="#FFFFFF">Order. Discipline.
Chain of command.</font>

332
00:22:30,766 --> 00:22:32,500
<font color="#FFFFFF">You're not at
university any longer.</font>

333
00:22:32,601 --> 00:22:35,712
<font color="#FFFFFF">You are a very small cog
in a very large system</font>

334
00:22:35,813 --> 00:22:39,082
<font color="#FFFFFF">and you will do
as your commanding officer instructs.</font>

335
00:22:42,944 --> 00:22:45,380
<font color="#FFFFFF">Who... Who is your
commanding officer?</font>

336
00:22:46,824 --> 00:22:50,593
<font color="#FFFFFF">Winston Churchill,
Number 10 Downing Street, London SW1.</font>

337
00:22:50,952 --> 00:22:54,263
<font color="#FFFFFF">You have a problem with my decision,
you can take it up with him.</font>

338
00:23:00,796 --> 00:23:03,397
<font color="#FFFFFF">Mr. Menzies. Mr. Menzies!</font>

339
00:23:06,844 --> 00:23:08,778
<font color="#FFFFFF">Are you going to London?</font>

340
00:23:09,805 --> 00:23:13,740
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Possibly.
- Would you deliver a letter for me?</font>

341
00:23:20,191 --> 00:23:22,584
<font color="#FFFFFF">Look, I'm sorry, but are you joking?</font>

342
00:23:22,984 --> 00:23:24,971
<font color="#FFFFFF">Churchill's put Alan in charge?</font>

343
00:23:25,070 --> 00:23:27,431
<font color="#FFFFFF">- This is a terrible idea.
- No, no, no...</font>

344
00:23:27,530 --> 00:23:29,965
<font color="#FFFFFF">So I can give these
men orders now?</font>

345
00:23:30,492 --> 00:23:31,935
<font color="#FFFFFF">I hate to say it but yes.</font>

346
00:23:32,036 --> 00:23:34,095
<font color="#FFFFFF">Excellent. Keith and Charles,
you're both fired.</font>

347
00:23:34,913 --> 00:23:36,731
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Excuse me?
- What?</font>

348
00:23:36,832 --> 00:23:39,484
<font color="#FFFFFF">You're mediocre linguists
and positively poor code-breakers.</font>

349
00:23:39,585 --> 00:23:42,070
<font color="#FFFFFF">Alan, you can't just fire
Keith and Charles.</font>

350
00:23:42,171 --> 00:23:43,447
<font color="#FFFFFF">Well, he just said I could.</font>

351
00:23:43,547 --> 00:23:45,074
<font color="#FFFFFF">No, I did no such thing.</font>

352
00:23:45,173 --> 00:23:46,691
<font color="#FFFFFF">But Churchill did.</font>

353
00:23:56,852 --> 00:23:58,452
<font color="#FFFFFF">Go to hell.</font>

354
00:24:03,526 --> 00:24:06,126
<font color="#FFFFFF">Well, this is inhuman.</font>

355
00:24:07,028 --> 00:24:08,546
<font color="#FFFFFF">Even for you.</font>

356
00:24:13,410 --> 00:24:15,303
<font color="#FFFFFF">Popular at school, were you?</font>

357
00:24:21,042 --> 00:24:22,611
<font color="#FFFFFF">The problem began, of course,</font>

358
00:24:22,711 --> 00:24:24,311
<font color="#FFFFFF">with the carrots.</font>

359
00:24:25,131 --> 00:24:26,647
<font color="#FFFFFF">The carrots are orange.</font>

360
00:24:27,633 --> 00:24:31,193
<font color="#FFFFFF">The peas are green.
They mustn't touch.</font>

361
00:24:56,162 --> 00:24:58,387
<font color="#FFFFFF">Do you know why people like violence?</font>

362
00:24:59,582 --> 00:25:02,599
<font color="#FFFFFF">It is because it feels good.</font>

363
00:25:04,002 --> 00:25:06,354
<font color="#FFFFFF">Humans find violence
deeply satisfying.</font>

364
00:25:08,089 --> 00:25:11,526
<font color="#FFFFFF">But remove the satisfaction</font>

365
00:25:12,428 --> 00:25:15,779
<font color="#FFFFFF">and the act becomes hollow.</font>

366
00:25:22,479 --> 00:25:23,788
<font color="#FFFFFF">Turing?</font>

367
00:25:24,606 --> 00:25:26,207
<font color="#FFFFFF">Come on.</font>

368
00:25:26,442 --> 00:25:27,916
<font color="#FFFFFF">Don't be such a kike about it.</font>

369
00:25:29,987 --> 00:25:31,962
<font color="#FFFFFF">Leave him to bloody rot.</font>

370
00:25:38,203 --> 00:25:40,689
<font color="#FFFFFF">I didn't learn this
on my own, of course.</font>

371
00:25:40,788 --> 00:25:42,265
<font color="#FFFFFF">I had help.</font>

372
00:25:43,666 --> 00:25:45,559
<font color="#FFFFFF">Christopher helped.</font>

373
00:25:48,005 --> 00:25:49,564
<font color="#FFFFFF">Alan, are you all right?</font>

374
00:25:55,511 --> 00:25:59,240
<font color="#FFFFFF">It's not my fault.
The carrots got in with the peas and...</font>

375
00:26:00,476 --> 00:26:02,461
<font color="#FFFFFF">I'm sorry, I won't let
them do it again.</font>

376
00:26:02,560 --> 00:26:04,077
<font color="#FFFFFF">They're getting worse.</font>

377
00:26:04,730 --> 00:26:07,133
<font color="#FFFFFF">They only beat me up
because I'm smarter than they are.</font>

378
00:26:07,232 --> 00:26:09,250
<font color="#FFFFFF">No, they beat you up
because you're different.</font>

379
00:26:09,817 --> 00:26:12,795
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Mother says I'm just an odd duck.
- And she's right.</font>

380
00:26:13,696 --> 00:26:15,432
<font color="#FFFFFF">But you know, Alan,</font>

381
00:26:15,531 --> 00:26:18,675
<font color="#FFFFFF">sometimes it's the very people
who no one imagines anything of</font>

382
00:26:19,411 --> 00:26:21,971
<font color="#FFFFFF">who do the things
no one can imagine.</font>

383
00:26:28,170 --> 00:26:29,936
<font color="#FFFFFF">So what do we do now?</font>

384
00:26:31,382 --> 00:26:35,192
<font color="#FFFFFF">- We're short on staff.
- Well, we, uh, we get more staff, then.</font>

385
00:26:35,927 --> 00:26:38,528
<font color="#FFFFFF">And how do you
propose to do that?</font>

386
00:29:06,369 --> 00:29:09,897
<font color="#FFFFFF">Erm, Alan Turing to
see Stewart Menzies.</font>

387
00:29:09,998 --> 00:29:11,598
<font color="#FFFFFF">Very good, sir.</font>

388
00:29:11,875 --> 00:29:13,318
<font color="#FFFFFF">So who are they?</font>

389
00:29:13,419 --> 00:29:16,904
<font color="#FFFFFF">Oh, all sorts, really.
A teacher. An engineer.</font>

390
00:29:17,005 --> 00:29:18,605
<font color="#FFFFFF">A handful of students.</font>

391
00:29:18,840 --> 00:29:20,326
<font color="#FFFFFF">And you think
they're qualified for Bletchley</font>

392
00:29:20,425 --> 00:29:22,027
<font color="#FFFFFF">'cause they're good
at crossword puzzles?</font>

393
00:29:22,094 --> 00:29:24,987
<font color="#FFFFFF">Well, they say they're good
and now we shall find out, won't we?</font>

394
00:29:26,515 --> 00:29:27,915
<font color="#FFFFFF">In order to aid your efforts,</font>

395
00:29:28,016 --> 00:29:30,586
<font color="#FFFFFF">there is, to the right of you,
a green scratch card book.</font>

396
00:29:30,685 --> 00:29:33,130
<font color="#FFFFFF">You are to make notes in that.
Gentlemen, you have six minutes</font>

397
00:29:33,230 --> 00:29:36,164
<font color="#FFFFFF">in which to complete the puzzle,
at which point I will...</font>

398
00:29:38,734 --> 00:29:40,336
<font color="#FFFFFF">Pardon me, ma'am,
this room's restricted.</font>

399
00:29:40,362 --> 00:29:43,130
<font color="#FFFFFF">Oh, apologies for my tardiness.
The bus caught a flat tyre.</font>

400
00:29:44,115 --> 00:29:45,799
<font color="#FFFFFF">May I continue, please?
Thank you.</font>

401
00:29:46,701 --> 00:29:49,438
<font color="#FFFFFF">- You're not allowed in here, ma'am.
- Oh, but I'm only a few minutes late...</font>

402
00:29:49,538 --> 00:29:52,941
<font color="#FFFFFF">The secretaries are to head upstairs.
This room's for the candidates.</font>

403
00:29:53,040 --> 00:29:55,142
<font color="#FFFFFF">May I get on with
this now, please?</font>

404
00:29:56,377 --> 00:29:58,364
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Uh, I am a candidate.
- For what position?</font>

405
00:29:58,463 --> 00:29:59,865
<font color="#FFFFFF">The letter didn't say, precisely.</font>

406
00:29:59,964 --> 00:30:01,450
<font color="#FFFFFF">Yes, the secretaries
are to head upstairs.</font>

407
00:30:01,549 --> 00:30:03,358
<font color="#FFFFFF">It did say that it
was top secret.</font>

408
00:30:03,759 --> 00:30:05,453
<font color="#FFFFFF">What is going on?</font>

409
00:30:05,554 --> 00:30:08,164
<font color="#FFFFFF">I... I solved a crossword puzzle
in the newspaper</font>

410
00:30:08,265 --> 00:30:09,665
<font color="#FFFFFF">and I got this letter saying</font>

411
00:30:09,766 --> 00:30:12,034
<font color="#FFFFFF">that I was a candidate
for some sort of mysterious job.</font>

412
00:30:12,227 --> 00:30:13,827
<font color="#FFFFFF">My name's Joan Clarke.</font>

413
00:30:13,979 --> 00:30:16,830
<font color="#FFFFFF">Miss, did you really solve
this puzzle yourself?</font>

414
00:30:19,734 --> 00:30:21,386
<font color="#FFFFFF">What makes you think
I couldn't solve the puzzle myself?</font>

415
00:30:21,487 --> 00:30:22,805
<font color="#FFFFFF">I'm really very good at...</font>

416
00:30:22,904 --> 00:30:24,226
<font color="#FFFFFF">Ma'am, I'll have to ask you to...</font>

417
00:30:24,280 --> 00:30:29,343
<font color="#FFFFFF">Miss Clarke, I find tardiness
under any circumstance unacceptable.</font>

418
00:30:32,748 --> 00:30:36,057
<font color="#FFFFFF">Take a seat so that
we may continue.</font>

419
00:30:39,171 --> 00:30:40,688
<font color="#FFFFFF">Thank you.</font>

420
00:30:41,757 --> 00:30:43,366
<font color="#FFFFFF">Now, as I was saying,</font>

421
00:30:43,467 --> 00:30:47,862
<font color="#FFFFFF">you have six minutes
to complete the task in front of you.</font>

422
00:30:48,763 --> 00:30:50,530
<font color="#FFFFFF">Erm, gentlemen, and lady...</font>

423
00:30:50,932 --> 00:30:52,407
<font color="#FFFFFF">begin.</font>

424
00:31:20,796 --> 00:31:22,270
<font color="#FFFFFF">Six minutes.</font>

425
00:31:23,298 --> 00:31:26,442
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Is that even possible?
- No, no. Takes me eight.</font>

426
00:31:27,051 --> 00:31:28,744
<font color="#FFFFFF">This isn't about
crossword puzzles.</font>

427
00:31:28,845 --> 00:31:31,946
<font color="#FFFFFF">It's about how one approaches
solving an impossible problem.</font>

428
00:31:32,974 --> 00:31:35,826
<font color="#FFFFFF">Do you tackle the whole thing
at once or divide it into small...</font>

429
00:31:38,020 --> 00:31:39,213
<font color="#FFFFFF">You've finished?</font>

430
00:31:39,314 --> 00:31:40,789
<font color="#FFFFFF">Yes.</font>

431
00:31:55,247 --> 00:31:56,971
<font color="#FFFFFF">Five minutes and 34 seconds.</font>

432
00:31:57,833 --> 00:31:59,683
<font color="#FFFFFF">You said to do it in under six.</font>

433
00:32:00,876 --> 00:32:02,435
<font color="#FFFFFF">Congratulations.</font>

434
00:32:02,878 --> 00:32:05,189
<font color="#FFFFFF">My warmest welcome
to His Majesty's Service.</font>

435
00:32:05,673 --> 00:32:07,826
<font color="#FFFFFF">If you speak a word
of what I'm about to show you,</font>

436
00:32:07,925 --> 00:32:09,777
<font color="#FFFFFF">you will be executed
for high treason.</font>

437
00:32:11,221 --> 00:32:13,414
<font color="#FFFFFF">You will lie to your friends,
your family</font>

438
00:32:13,515 --> 00:32:16,616
<font color="#FFFFFF">and everyone you meet
about what it is you really do.</font>

439
00:32:18,436 --> 00:32:20,788
<font color="#FFFFFF">And what is it that
we're really doing?</font>

440
00:32:21,022 --> 00:32:24,290
<font color="#FFFFFF">We're going to break an unbreakable
Nazi code and win the war.</font>

441
00:32:25,693 --> 00:32:27,294
<font color="#FFFFFF">Oh.</font>

442
00:32:37,038 --> 00:32:38,847
<font color="#FFFFFF">What's that you're reading?</font>

443
00:32:39,875 --> 00:32:42,852
<font color="#FFFFFF">- It's about cryptography.
- Like secret messages?</font>

444
00:32:44,211 --> 00:32:47,314
<font color="#FFFFFF">Not secret.
That's the brilliant part.</font>

445
00:32:47,923 --> 00:32:50,651
<font color="#FFFFFF">Messages that anyone can see
but no one knows what they mean</font>

446
00:32:50,885 --> 00:32:52,653
<font color="#FFFFFF">unless you have the key.</font>

447
00:32:58,268 --> 00:33:00,661
<font color="#FFFFFF">How's that different
from talking?</font>

448
00:33:01,480 --> 00:33:03,214
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Talking?
- When people talk to each other,</font>

449
00:33:03,315 --> 00:33:06,175
<font color="#FFFFFF">they never say what they mean,
they say something else.</font>

450
00:33:06,276 --> 00:33:09,179
<font color="#FFFFFF">And you're expected
to just know what they mean.</font>

451
00:33:09,278 --> 00:33:10,921
<font color="#FFFFFF">Only I never do.</font>

452
00:33:11,323 --> 00:33:12,882
<font color="#FFFFFF">So...</font>

453
00:33:13,282 --> 00:33:14,924
<font color="#FFFFFF">how's that different?</font>

454
00:33:16,243 --> 00:33:19,387
<font color="#FFFFFF">Alan, I have a funny feeling
you're going to be very good at this.</font>

455
00:33:45,440 --> 00:33:46,957
<font color="#FFFFFF">Goodnight, Alan.</font>

456
00:33:51,863 --> 00:33:53,463
<font color="#FFFFFF">Goodnight.</font>

457
00:34:12,800 --> 00:34:15,485
<font color="#FFFFFF">Careful, will you? It's not a toy.</font>

458
00:34:15,846 --> 00:34:17,905
<font color="#FFFFFF">Funny. Looks like a toy.</font>

459
00:34:18,181 --> 00:34:22,242
<font color="#FFFFFF">Bloody great £100,000 one.
Your new minion's arrived.</font>

460
00:34:22,978 --> 00:34:25,411
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Jack Good. We met...
- Well, where's Miss Clarke?</font>

461
00:34:29,067 --> 00:34:30,635
<font color="#FFFFFF">Lovely, isn't he?</font>

462
00:34:30,735 --> 00:34:35,389
<font color="#FFFFFF">It's not just a usual
humdrum production mill factory.</font>

463
00:34:35,489 --> 00:34:40,353
<font color="#FFFFFF">I mean, well, as I was saying,
it's a very important radio factory.</font>

464
00:34:40,454 --> 00:34:42,271
<font color="#FFFFFF">It's not, actually.</font>

465
00:34:42,371 --> 00:34:47,809
<font color="#FFFFFF">On the spectrum of radio
factories, this one is particularly...</font>

466
00:34:58,512 --> 00:35:01,208
<font color="#FFFFFF">Why are you not at Bletchley?</font>

467
00:35:01,307 --> 00:35:03,876
<font color="#FFFFFF">Thank you so much for your visit,
Mr. Turing.</font>

468
00:35:03,976 --> 00:35:06,369
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Was your trip pleasant?
- Gather your things and let's go.</font>

469
00:35:07,146 --> 00:35:09,373
<font color="#FFFFFF">I'm sorry but I'm unable
to accept your offer.</font>

470
00:35:09,565 --> 00:35:13,043
<font color="#FFFFFF">We feel that such a position
would hardly be appropriate.</font>

471
00:35:13,402 --> 00:35:15,713
<font color="#FFFFFF">You earned a double first
in mathematics.</font>

472
00:35:15,864 --> 00:35:18,673
<font color="#FFFFFF">But sadly, wasn't granted
the opportunity to become a fellow.</font>

473
00:35:19,034 --> 00:35:20,759
<font color="#FFFFFF">You belong at Bletchley.</font>

474
00:35:21,244 --> 00:35:24,929
<font color="#FFFFFF">I'm sorry, but for someone
in my position to live, to...</font>

475
00:35:25,456 --> 00:35:28,735
<font color="#FFFFFF">to work in a radio factory
so far from home,</font>

476
00:35:28,835 --> 00:35:32,228
<font color="#FFFFFF">with all your men,
erm, it would be...</font>

477
00:35:33,715 --> 00:35:35,231
<font color="#FFFFFF">indecorous.</font>

478
00:35:36,802 --> 00:35:39,903
<font color="#FFFFFF">What in the world
does that even mean?</font>

479
00:35:44,601 --> 00:35:48,922
<font color="#FFFFFF">We have a group of young ladies
who tend to all of our clerical tasks.</font>

480
00:35:49,021 --> 00:35:50,840
<font color="#FFFFFF">Assistants, translators.</font>

481
00:35:50,940 --> 00:35:53,552
<font color="#FFFFFF">They live, erm,
together in town.</font>

482
00:35:53,652 --> 00:35:57,128
<font color="#FFFFFF">Would that be a
more suitable environment?</font>

483
00:35:57,697 --> 00:36:01,592
<font color="#FFFFFF">Hmm. So... So I would be working
amongst these women?</font>

484
00:36:01,742 --> 00:36:03,260
<font color="#FFFFFF">Yes.</font>

485
00:36:06,373 --> 00:36:07,648
<font color="#FFFFFF">Wonderful ladies.</font>

486
00:36:07,748 --> 00:36:11,152
<font color="#FFFFFF">They even organise social events
at St. Martin's church down the road.</font>

487
00:36:11,253 --> 00:36:13,896
<font color="#FFFFFF">Really, the whole
thing is quite, er,</font>

488
00:36:14,172 --> 00:36:16,231
<font color="#FFFFFF">um, decorous.</font>

489
00:36:21,221 --> 00:36:23,789
<font color="#FFFFFF">Now, you won't have
proper security clearance, of course,</font>

490
00:36:23,889 --> 00:36:26,460
<font color="#FFFFFF">so we'll have to
improvise things a bit.</font>

491
00:36:26,559 --> 00:36:28,003
<font color="#FFFFFF">Why are you helping me?</font>

492
00:36:28,103 --> 00:36:31,465
<font color="#FFFFFF">Because there is only one thing that
matters in this entire world right now,</font>

493
00:36:31,565 --> 00:36:33,581
<font color="#FFFFFF">do you understand?
And that is breaking Enigma.</font>

494
00:36:33,817 --> 00:36:35,376
<font color="#FFFFFF">But... But Mr. Turing...</font>

495
00:36:37,403 --> 00:36:39,003
<font color="#FFFFFF">Why are you helping me?</font>

496
00:36:39,905 --> 00:36:41,507
<font color="#FFFFFF">Oh, um...</font>

497
00:36:43,451 --> 00:36:46,061
<font color="#FFFFFF">Sometimes it's the very people
who no one imagines anything of</font>

498
00:36:46,161 --> 00:36:49,264
<font color="#FFFFFF">who do the things
that no one can imagine.</font>

499
00:37:07,976 --> 00:37:09,534
<font color="#FFFFFF">Sir.</font>

500
00:37:09,978 --> 00:37:13,914
<font color="#FFFFFF">- What this?
- Alan Turing's classified military file.</font>

501
00:37:15,025 --> 00:37:16,833
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Bloody empty.
- Exactly.</font>

502
00:37:17,443 --> 00:37:19,753
<font color="#FFFFFF">- It's an empty manila envelope.
- Yeah.</font>

503
00:37:21,114 --> 00:37:23,266
<font color="#FFFFFF">You've cracked the case wide open, then,
haven't you?</font>

504
00:37:23,365 --> 00:37:25,726
<font color="#FFFFFF">Alan Turing's war records
aren't just classified,</font>

505
00:37:25,827 --> 00:37:27,385
<font color="#FFFFFF">they're non-existent.</font>

506
00:37:28,038 --> 00:37:31,817
<font color="#FFFFFF">That means someone's got rid of them,
erased them, burnt them.</font>

507
00:37:31,916 --> 00:37:35,143
<font color="#FFFFFF">And that same person broke
into his house and stole nothing?</font>

508
00:37:36,503 --> 00:37:38,438
<font color="#FFFFFF">Guy Burgess and Donald Maclean.</font>

509
00:37:39,090 --> 00:37:41,983
<font color="#FFFFFF">- What, the spies from the papers?
- Soviet spies.</font>

510
00:37:42,510 --> 00:37:44,945
<font color="#FFFFFF">But first they were professors,
weren't they?</font>

511
00:37:45,597 --> 00:37:48,375
<font color="#FFFFFF">Radicalised at Cambridge,
then they joined the Communist Party,</font>

512
00:37:48,474 --> 00:37:49,626
<font color="#FFFFFF">then the Foreign Office,</font>

513
00:37:49,726 --> 00:37:51,920
<font color="#FFFFFF">then leaked information to Stalin
during the war.</font>

514
00:37:52,019 --> 00:37:54,505
<font color="#FFFFFF">Now, can you think of anyone else
we know who was at Cambridge,</font>

515
00:37:54,606 --> 00:37:57,958
<font color="#FFFFFF">then took up something murky
and top secret when the war broke out?</font>

516
00:37:58,275 --> 00:38:01,461
<font color="#FFFFFF">You think this Alan Turing
might be a Soviet agent?</font>

517
00:38:01,987 --> 00:38:06,382
<font color="#FFFFFF">I think something very serious
is happening right here under our noses.</font>

518
00:38:07,409 --> 00:38:10,012
<font color="#FFFFFF">Wouldn't you like
to find out what it is?</font>

519
00:38:42,445 --> 00:38:45,047
<font color="#FFFFFF">Welcome, ladies.
If you'd like to follow me.</font>

520
00:38:47,242 --> 00:38:50,019
<font color="#FFFFFF">Some people thought
we were at war with the Germans.</font>

521
00:38:50,119 --> 00:38:51,146
<font color="#FFFFFF">Incorrect.</font>

522
00:38:51,246 --> 00:38:53,398
<font color="#FFFFFF">We were at war with the clock.</font>

523
00:38:53,498 --> 00:38:55,974
<font color="#FFFFFF">Britain was literally
starving to death.</font>

524
00:38:56,751 --> 00:39:01,188
<font color="#FFFFFF">The Americans sent over 100,000 tonnes
of food every week</font>

525
00:39:01,463 --> 00:39:04,742
<font color="#FFFFFF">and every week the Germans would
send our desperately needed bread</font>

526
00:39:04,842 --> 00:39:06,452
<font color="#FFFFFF">to the bottom of the ocean.</font>

527
00:39:06,552 --> 00:39:10,155
<font color="#FFFFFF">Our daily failure was announced
at the chimes of midnight.</font>

528
00:39:10,431 --> 00:39:13,909
<font color="#FFFFFF">And the sound would haunt
our unwelcome dreams.</font>

529
00:39:14,476 --> 00:39:16,411
<font color="#FFFFFF">Tick, tock.</font>

530
00:39:16,855 --> 00:39:18,047
<font color="#FFFFFF">Tick.</font>

531
00:39:24,528 --> 00:39:26,130
<font color="#FFFFFF">Damn it!</font>

532
00:39:28,365 --> 00:39:30,634
<font color="#FFFFFF">- What just happened?
- Midnight.</font>

533
00:39:31,077 --> 00:39:33,688
<font color="#FFFFFF">All the work we've done today
is useless.</font>

534
00:39:33,788 --> 00:39:35,429
<font color="#FFFFFF">Oh, but don't worry,
we've a few hours</font>

535
00:39:35,539 --> 00:39:37,891
<font color="#FFFFFF">before tomorrow's messages
start flooding in,</font>

536
00:39:38,501 --> 00:39:40,393
<font color="#FFFFFF">then we start all over again.</font>

537
00:39:42,380 --> 00:39:44,740
<font color="#FFFFFF">- From scratch.
- I'm so sick of this.</font>

538
00:39:44,840 --> 00:39:47,702
<font color="#FFFFFF">Four hours rewiring
his plugboard matrix.</font>

539
00:39:47,802 --> 00:39:50,403
<font color="#FFFFFF">Three hours yesterday
on his rotor positions.</font>

540
00:39:50,679 --> 00:39:53,407
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Don't go over there.
- Look, John, no.</font>

541
00:39:53,516 --> 00:39:56,460
<font color="#FFFFFF">If this job wasn't already impossible
before, it bloody well is now.</font>

542
00:39:56,561 --> 00:39:58,077
<font color="#FFFFFF">Hugh, don't.</font>

543
00:40:06,612 --> 00:40:08,963
<font color="#FFFFFF">Damn you and your
useless machine.</font>

544
00:40:09,824 --> 00:40:13,135
<font color="#FFFFFF">My machine is how we
are going to win.</font>

545
00:40:13,244 --> 00:40:14,760
<font color="#FFFFFF">Really?</font>

546
00:40:15,204 --> 00:40:16,762
<font color="#FFFFFF">This machine?</font>

547
00:40:17,873 --> 00:40:20,266
<font color="#FFFFFF">Are you talking about
this bloody machine?</font>

548
00:40:20,418 --> 00:40:21,860
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Hugh!
- Hugh, don't! Don't!</font>

549
00:40:21,960 --> 00:40:24,364
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Stop!
- You arrogant bastard.</font>

550
00:40:24,463 --> 00:40:25,907
<font color="#FFFFFF">You could help us.</font>

551
00:40:26,007 --> 00:40:28,358
<font color="#FFFFFF">You could make this go faster
but you won't.</font>

552
00:40:30,385 --> 00:40:31,987
<font color="#FFFFFF">Get off.</font>

553
00:40:37,559 --> 00:40:39,077
<font color="#FFFFFF">He's right, Alan.</font>

554
00:40:41,063 --> 00:40:45,041
<font color="#FFFFFF">There are actual soldiers out there
trying to win an actual war.</font>

555
00:40:45,818 --> 00:40:48,637
<font color="#FFFFFF">My brother protects
food convoys in the Navy.</font>

556
00:40:48,737 --> 00:40:51,391
<font color="#FFFFFF">My cousins fly RAF patrols.</font>

557
00:40:51,490 --> 00:40:56,135
<font color="#FFFFFF">All my friends, they're all making
a difference while we just</font>

558
00:40:56,788 --> 00:40:59,931
<font color="#FFFFFF">while away our days
producing nothing.</font>

559
00:41:01,416 --> 00:41:02,976
<font color="#FFFFFF">Because of you.</font>

560
00:41:04,295 --> 00:41:07,981
<font color="#FFFFFF">My machine will work.</font>

561
00:41:09,842 --> 00:41:11,485
<font color="#FFFFFF">Come on, Peter.</font>

562
00:41:51,425 --> 00:41:53,025
<font color="#FFFFFF">Okay.</font>

563
00:42:22,581 --> 00:42:24,766
<font color="#FFFFFF">Joan!</font>

564
00:42:50,652 --> 00:42:53,692
<font color="#FFFFFF">Could you have made a bit more noise?
I'm not quite sure my landlady woke up.</font>

565
00:42:53,737 --> 00:42:56,005
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Oh, sorry.
- Oh, uh, look.</font>

566
00:42:56,365 --> 00:42:59,592
<font color="#FFFFFF">I think that's the best I can do.
No male visitors after dark.</font>

567
00:43:00,619 --> 00:43:04,222
<font color="#FFFFFF">- So, what did you bring me?
- Erm...</font>

568
00:43:04,581 --> 00:43:06,599
<font color="#FFFFFF">- There you go.
- Here.</font>

569
00:43:07,876 --> 00:43:09,686
<font color="#FFFFFF">Some men try flowers, you know.</font>

570
00:43:10,170 --> 00:43:14,106
<font color="#FFFFFF">These are actual decrypted Enigma
messages direct from Nazi High Command.</font>

571
00:43:16,260 --> 00:43:19,445
<font color="#FFFFFF">"0600 hours, weather
today is clear."</font>

572
00:43:19,597 --> 00:43:21,782
<font color="#FFFFFF">"Rain in the evening.
Heil Hitler."</font>

573
00:43:22,849 --> 00:43:25,730
<font color="#FFFFFF">Well, clearly that vital piece of
information is going to win us the war.</font>

574
00:43:25,811 --> 00:43:27,996
<font color="#FFFFFF">It's the relationship
between the encrypted</font>

575
00:43:28,273 --> 00:43:30,791
<font color="#FFFFFF">and decrypted messages
that interests me.</font>

576
00:43:31,483 --> 00:43:34,637
<font color="#FFFFFF">Can we find a clue here
that we can build into Christopher?</font>

577
00:43:34,737 --> 00:43:37,380
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Who's Christopher?
- Oh, he's my machine.</font>

578
00:43:38,199 --> 00:43:39,757
<font color="#FFFFFF">You named him?</font>

579
00:43:40,367 --> 00:43:41,927
<font color="#FFFFFF">Is that a bad name?</font>

580
00:43:43,161 --> 00:43:44,721
<font color="#FFFFFF">No.</font>

581
00:43:45,623 --> 00:43:47,139
<font color="#FFFFFF">No, never mind.</font>

582
00:43:53,672 --> 00:43:55,773
<font color="#FFFFFF">Are you trying to build
your universal machine?</font>

583
00:43:58,094 --> 00:43:59,786
<font color="#FFFFFF">I read your paper at university.</font>

584
00:43:59,887 --> 00:44:02,039
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Is it already being taught?
- No.</font>

585
00:44:02,139 --> 00:44:04,666
<font color="#FFFFFF">No. No, I was precocious.</font>

586
00:44:04,766 --> 00:44:08,670
<font color="#FFFFFF">So, you theorised a machine
that could solve any problem?</font>

587
00:44:08,771 --> 00:44:10,923
<font color="#FFFFFF">It didn't just do one thing,
it did everything?</font>

588
00:44:11,023 --> 00:44:13,134
<font color="#FFFFFF">It wasn't just programmable,
it was re-programmable?</font>

589
00:44:13,233 --> 00:44:14,418
<font color="#FFFFFF">Mmm.</font>

590
00:44:14,943 --> 00:44:16,795
<font color="#FFFFFF">Is that your idea
behind Christopher?</font>

591
00:44:18,030 --> 00:44:22,184
<font color="#FFFFFF">Human brains can compute large sums
very quickly, even Hugh can do that,</font>

592
00:44:22,284 --> 00:44:24,302
<font color="#FFFFFF">but I want Christopher
to be smarter.</font>

593
00:44:25,079 --> 00:44:29,099
<font color="#FFFFFF">To make a calculation
and then to determine what to do next.</font>

594
00:44:30,043 --> 00:44:31,601
<font color="#FFFFFF">Like a person does.</font>

595
00:44:32,420 --> 00:44:34,019
<font color="#FFFFFF">Think of it.</font>

596
00:44:34,213 --> 00:44:35,856
<font color="#FFFFFF">An electrical brain.</font>

597
00:44:36,340 --> 00:44:37,898
<font color="#FFFFFF">A digital computer.</font>

598
00:44:39,052 --> 00:44:40,568
<font color="#FFFFFF">Digital computer?</font>

599
00:44:42,221 --> 00:44:43,822
<font color="#FFFFFF">Hmm.</font>

600
00:44:57,402 --> 00:44:58,961
<font color="#FFFFFF">What's going on?</font>

601
00:44:59,405 --> 00:45:00,922
<font color="#FFFFFF">What's happening?</font>

602
00:45:01,782 --> 00:45:03,684
<font color="#FFFFFF">- No, no, no. Don't touch that.
- Stay back.</font>

603
00:45:03,784 --> 00:45:05,010
<font color="#FFFFFF">That's my desk.</font>

604
00:45:06,079 --> 00:45:09,148
<font color="#FFFFFF">Thank goodness. I'd hate to think
we were searching the wrong one.</font>

605
00:45:09,248 --> 00:45:10,891
<font color="#FFFFFF">What are you doing?
What's going on?</font>

606
00:45:12,001 --> 00:45:14,152
<font color="#FFFFFF">There is a spy in
Bletchley Park.</font>

607
00:45:14,253 --> 00:45:16,938
<font color="#FFFFFF">The Navy thinks that one of us
is a Soviet double agent, Alan.</font>

608
00:45:17,422 --> 00:45:18,940
<font color="#FFFFFF">Why?</font>

609
00:45:19,967 --> 00:45:22,652
<font color="#FFFFFF">Our boys intercepted this
on its way to Moscow.</font>

610
00:45:22,762 --> 00:45:24,320
<font color="#FFFFFF">Look familiar?</font>

611
00:45:28,226 --> 00:45:29,626
<font color="#FFFFFF">It's a Beale cipher.</font>

612
00:45:29,726 --> 00:45:32,954
<font color="#FFFFFF">Encrypted with a phrase from a book
or a poem or...</font>

613
00:45:38,527 --> 00:45:40,085
<font color="#FFFFFF">You...</font>

614
00:45:40,780 --> 00:45:43,465
<font color="#FFFFFF">You don't seriously think I did this,
do you?</font>

615
00:45:44,659 --> 00:45:46,259
<font color="#FFFFFF">Double agents are such bastards.</font>

616
00:45:47,077 --> 00:45:51,106
<font color="#FFFFFF">Isolated loners.
No attachments to friends or family.</font>

617
00:45:51,206 --> 00:45:52,849
<font color="#FFFFFF">Arrogant.</font>

618
00:45:53,251 --> 00:45:54,934
<font color="#FFFFFF">Know anybody like that?</font>

619
00:45:58,297 --> 00:45:59,824
<font color="#FFFFFF">I...</font>

620
00:45:59,923 --> 00:46:02,409
<font color="#FFFFFF">Hmm. I know you don't like me</font>

621
00:46:02,510 --> 00:46:05,737
<font color="#FFFFFF">but that does not
make me a Soviet spy.</font>

622
00:46:06,639 --> 00:46:08,155
<font color="#FFFFFF">Nothing out of the
ordinary, sir.</font>

623
00:46:10,434 --> 00:46:12,494
<font color="#FFFFFF">Really? Hmm, all right.</font>

624
00:46:15,440 --> 00:46:17,592
<font color="#FFFFFF">The Home Office
may be protecting you now</font>

625
00:46:17,692 --> 00:46:19,918
<font color="#FFFFFF">but sooner or later,
you will make a mistake.</font>

626
00:46:21,237 --> 00:46:23,170
<font color="#FFFFFF">And I needn't bother firing you.</font>

627
00:46:23,405 --> 00:46:25,548
<font color="#FFFFFF">They will hang you for treason.</font>

628
00:46:47,221 --> 00:46:48,780
<font color="#FFFFFF">Hello.</font>

629
00:46:50,307 --> 00:46:51,958
<font color="#FFFFFF">I heard about what happened.</font>

630
00:46:52,059 --> 00:46:54,411
<font color="#FFFFFF">It's all the girls in Hut 3
can talk about.</font>

631
00:46:56,771 --> 00:46:59,039
<font color="#FFFFFF">I have an idea of what
might cheer you up.</font>

632
00:47:03,445 --> 00:47:05,597
<font color="#FFFFFF">So, because no letter can be
encoded as itself,</font>

633
00:47:05,697 --> 00:47:08,577
<font color="#FFFFFF">there's already a handful of settings
that can be rejected at the outset.</font>

634
00:47:13,706 --> 00:47:15,775
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Is that your team?
- Uh, yes.</font>

635
00:47:15,875 --> 00:47:17,318
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Shall we say hello?
- No.</font>

636
00:47:17,418 --> 00:47:18,934
<font color="#FFFFFF">Hello.</font>

637
00:47:19,170 --> 00:47:21,061
<font color="#FFFFFF">I told you not to do that.</font>

638
00:47:22,632 --> 00:47:24,074
<font color="#FFFFFF">Alan.</font>

639
00:47:24,175 --> 00:47:26,577
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Uh, Hugh, hello.
- Didn't know you drank.</font>

640
00:47:26,677 --> 00:47:28,871
<font color="#FFFFFF">He doesn't, really.
He just sort of sips at the foam.</font>

641
00:47:28,971 --> 00:47:30,610
<font color="#FFFFFF">I'll let you
into a little secret, Miss...</font>

642
00:47:30,889 --> 00:47:32,333
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Clarke.
- Miss Clarke.</font>

643
00:47:32,432 --> 00:47:34,951
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Please.
- Foam's my favourite part, too.</font>

644
00:47:35,268 --> 00:47:37,547
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Is it really?
- Come and join us for a drink.</font>

645
00:47:37,646 --> 00:47:40,373
<font color="#FFFFFF">- We'll be there in a moment.
- Miss Clarke.</font>

646
00:47:47,030 --> 00:47:48,349
<font color="#FFFFFF">Well, he likes you.</font>

647
00:47:48,449 --> 00:47:50,050
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Yes.
- You, uh...</font>

648
00:47:51,452 --> 00:47:53,844
<font color="#FFFFFF">You got him to like you.</font>

649
00:47:55,039 --> 00:47:56,806
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Yes.
- Why?</font>

650
00:47:57,666 --> 00:47:59,152
<font color="#FFFFFF">Because I'm a woman
in a man's job</font>

651
00:47:59,251 --> 00:48:01,561
<font color="#FFFFFF">and I don't have the luxury
of being an arse.</font>

652
00:48:02,922 --> 00:48:05,940
<font color="#FFFFFF">Alan, it doesn't matter
how smart you are,</font>

653
00:48:06,217 --> 00:48:08,108
<font color="#FFFFFF">Enigma is always smarter.</font>

654
00:48:09,344 --> 00:48:12,030
<font color="#FFFFFF">If you really want to
solve your puzzle,</font>

655
00:48:12,181 --> 00:48:14,141
<font color="#FFFFFF">then you're going to need
all the help you can get</font>

656
00:48:14,224 --> 00:48:18,286
<font color="#FFFFFF">and they are not going to help you
if they do not like you.</font>

657
00:48:25,777 --> 00:48:27,179
<font color="#FFFFFF">What are those?</font>

658
00:48:27,280 --> 00:48:29,764
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Apples.
- No.</font>

659
00:48:29,864 --> 00:48:32,309
<font color="#FFFFFF">Oh, they really are. Um, I've...</font>

660
00:48:32,409 --> 00:48:35,052
<font color="#FFFFFF">Well, Miss Clarke...
Joan, actually, um,</font>

661
00:48:36,289 --> 00:48:37,981
<font color="#FFFFFF">said that it would be nice</font>

662
00:48:38,081 --> 00:48:40,275
<font color="#FFFFFF">if I was to bring
you all something.</font>

663
00:48:40,376 --> 00:48:42,195
<font color="#FFFFFF">So here we are.</font>

664
00:48:42,295 --> 00:48:44,186
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Thank you.
- I like apples.</font>

665
00:48:45,380 --> 00:48:46,824
<font color="#FFFFFF">My best to Miss Clarke.</font>

666
00:48:46,923 --> 00:48:51,318
<font color="#FFFFFF">Uh, there are two people in a wood
and, um, they run into a bear.</font>

667
00:48:51,637 --> 00:48:53,914
<font color="#FFFFFF">The first person gets down
on his knees to pray.</font>

668
00:48:54,014 --> 00:48:55,875
<font color="#FFFFFF">The second person
starts lacing up his boots.</font>

669
00:48:55,974 --> 00:48:57,793
<font color="#FFFFFF">The first person asks
the second person,</font>

670
00:48:57,893 --> 00:49:01,047
<font color="#FFFFFF">"My dear friend, what are you doing?
You can't outrun a bear."</font>

671
00:49:01,146 --> 00:49:02,797
<font color="#FFFFFF">To which the second
person responds,</font>

672
00:49:02,898 --> 00:49:06,583
<font color="#FFFFFF">"I don't have to,
I only have to outrun you."</font>

673
00:49:17,246 --> 00:49:20,233
<font color="#FFFFFF">I'll be with Christopher
if anyone needs me.</font>

674
00:49:20,333 --> 00:49:24,853
<font color="#FFFFFF">If we assume that the square
root of two is a rational number,</font>

675
00:49:25,670 --> 00:49:30,650
<font color="#FFFFFF">then we can say that
the square root of two is A over B,</font>

676
00:49:31,635 --> 00:49:34,320
<font color="#FFFFFF">where A and B are whole numbers</font>

677
00:49:34,847 --> 00:49:37,282
<font color="#FFFFFF">and B is not zero.</font>

678
00:49:37,474 --> 00:49:40,744
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Mr. Turing, passing notes, are we?
- No, sir.</font>

679
00:49:46,900 --> 00:49:50,554
<font color="#FFFFFF">Only Turing would pass notes
written in gibberish.</font>

680
00:49:55,742 --> 00:49:57,186
<font color="#FFFFFF">All right, gentlemen.</font>

681
00:49:57,286 --> 00:50:00,012
<font color="#FFFFFF">Do not forget your algebra
over the break.</font>

682
00:50:01,081 --> 00:50:02,983
<font color="#FFFFFF">Have a pleasant holiday.</font>

683
00:50:03,083 --> 00:50:06,518
<font color="#FFFFFF">And we'll resume your irrationals
when you return.</font>

684
00:50:38,244 --> 00:50:39,677
<font color="#FFFFFF">Mmm.</font>

685
00:50:41,746 --> 00:50:44,567
<font color="#FFFFFF">But Euler's Theorem
gives you that immediately.</font>

686
00:50:44,666 --> 00:50:46,434
<font color="#FFFFFF">Erm...</font>

687
00:50:55,677 --> 00:50:57,653
<font color="#FFFFFF">Here, look at this.</font>

688
00:50:59,931 --> 00:51:02,460
<font color="#FFFFFF">If you run the wires across
the plugboard matrix diagonally,</font>

689
00:51:02,559 --> 00:51:05,369
<font color="#FFFFFF">it will eliminate rotor positions
500 times faster.</font>

690
00:51:06,688 --> 00:51:10,708
<font color="#FFFFFF">That's, uh,
actually not an entirely terrible idea.</font>

691
00:51:13,278 --> 00:51:15,003
<font color="#FFFFFF">I think that was Alan
for "thank you".</font>

692
00:51:18,742 --> 00:51:22,052
<font color="#FFFFFF">- That's my sandwich.
- You don't like sandwiches.</font>

693
00:51:36,635 --> 00:51:38,152
<font color="#FFFFFF">Are you nervous?</font>

694
00:52:00,909 --> 00:52:02,677
<font color="#FFFFFF">What happens now?</font>

695
00:52:04,079 --> 00:52:07,556
<font color="#FFFFFF">Well, it should work out
the day's Enigma settings.</font>

696
00:52:22,389 --> 00:52:23,947
<font color="#FFFFFF">How long?</font>

697
00:52:41,826 --> 00:52:44,769
<font color="#FFFFFF">The German Army
has fanned out across Europe,</font>

698
00:52:44,869 --> 00:52:48,815
<font color="#FFFFFF">from Poland to Serbia,
Lithuania to Denmark, Norway to France.</font>

699
00:52:48,916 --> 00:52:52,945
<font color="#FFFFFF">The Nazi flag now flies from more
than two dozen national capitals.</font>

700
00:52:53,045 --> 00:52:57,065
<font color="#FFFFFF">Their campaign mounts in fury
as a free Europe crumbles.</font>

701
00:53:38,007 --> 00:53:39,887
<font color="#FFFFFF">Oh, it's still going.</font>

702
00:53:39,967 --> 00:53:42,025
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Good morning, sir.
- Morning, Margaret.</font>

703
00:53:42,219 --> 00:53:45,445
<font color="#FFFFFF">Gears keep spinning on and on.
Rotors on and on.</font>

704
00:53:46,056 --> 00:53:47,572
<font color="#FFFFFF">It's endless.</font>

705
00:53:48,266 --> 00:53:51,878
<font color="#FFFFFF">- With no result in sight?
- No.</font>

706
00:54:05,326 --> 00:54:06,800
<font color="#FFFFFF">Turing.</font>

707
00:54:18,755 --> 00:54:20,773
<font color="#FFFFFF">Turing, open the bloody door.</font>

708
00:54:21,090 --> 00:54:22,608
<font color="#FFFFFF">No. No.</font>

709
00:54:24,552 --> 00:54:26,454
<font color="#FFFFFF">Open the door or
we'll break it down.</font>

710
00:54:26,554 --> 00:54:28,331
<font color="#FFFFFF">I can't let you in.</font>

711
00:54:28,431 --> 00:54:30,115
<font color="#FFFFFF">I cannot let you interfere.</font>

712
00:54:30,516 --> 00:54:32,034
<font color="#FFFFFF">Go on, then.</font>

713
00:54:39,443 --> 00:54:40,960
<font color="#FFFFFF">Turn that thing off!</font>

714
00:54:41,362 --> 00:54:43,295
<font color="#FFFFFF">No. Don't, please.</font>

715
00:54:43,447 --> 00:54:45,349
<font color="#FFFFFF">Please, please, please!</font>

716
00:54:45,449 --> 00:54:48,300
<font color="#FFFFFF">No. No, don't! No, no!</font>

717
00:54:52,206 --> 00:54:56,809
<font color="#FFFFFF">Well, then, it seems that your great
big expensive machine doesn't work.</font>

718
00:54:58,128 --> 00:54:59,644
<font color="#FFFFFF">It does.</font>

719
00:55:00,047 --> 00:55:03,315
<font color="#FFFFFF">Wonderful.
So you've broken Enigma, then?</font>

720
00:55:03,884 --> 00:55:05,485
<font color="#FFFFFF">It was just...</font>

721
00:55:06,302 --> 00:55:08,320
<font color="#FFFFFF">Still working.</font>

722
00:55:09,472 --> 00:55:11,490
<font color="#FFFFFF">This is my associate
from the Home Office.</font>

723
00:55:12,101 --> 00:55:15,378
<font color="#FFFFFF">You see,
£100,000 is rather a lot of money</font>

724
00:55:15,478 --> 00:55:17,882
<font color="#FFFFFF">and he's here to see
what you have to show for it.</font>

725
00:55:17,981 --> 00:55:21,342
<font color="#FFFFFF">You will never understand</font>

726
00:55:21,443 --> 00:55:25,045
<font color="#FFFFFF">the importance of what
I am creating here!</font>

727
00:55:26,657 --> 00:55:29,342
<font color="#FFFFFF">Have you decrypted
any German messages?</font>

728
00:55:30,119 --> 00:55:31,719
<font color="#FFFFFF">A single one?</font>

729
00:55:32,788 --> 00:55:35,722
<font color="#FFFFFF">Can you point to anything at all
that you've achieved?</font>

730
00:55:36,333 --> 00:55:37,902
<font color="#FFFFFF">Hmm.</font>

731
00:55:38,001 --> 00:55:41,896
<font color="#FFFFFF">Your funding is up
and our patience has expired.</font>

732
00:55:42,297 --> 00:55:46,534
<font color="#FFFFFF">It's with such great pleasure
that I am finally able to say this.</font>

733
00:55:46,635 --> 00:55:48,902
<font color="#FFFFFF">Alan Turing, you're fired.</font>

734
00:55:50,264 --> 00:55:52,697
<font color="#FFFFFF">Please escort Mr. Turing
from the premises.</font>

735
00:55:53,976 --> 00:55:55,576
<font color="#FFFFFF">No.</font>

736
00:55:57,103 --> 00:55:58,913
<font color="#FFFFFF">I beg your pardon?</font>

737
00:56:03,610 --> 00:56:06,211
<font color="#FFFFFF">If you fire Alan,</font>

738
00:56:07,322 --> 00:56:09,548
<font color="#FFFFFF">well, then, you'll
have to fire me, too.</font>

739
00:56:09,949 --> 00:56:11,467
<font color="#FFFFFF">What on earth are you saying?</font>

740
00:56:12,327 --> 00:56:13,938
<font color="#FFFFFF">Trust me when I tell
you there is no one</font>

741
00:56:14,038 --> 00:56:16,472
<font color="#FFFFFF">who would rather say this
less than I do but...</font>

742
00:56:18,208 --> 00:56:21,362
<font color="#FFFFFF">he's right. Alan is right.</font>

743
00:56:21,461 --> 00:56:25,648
<font color="#FFFFFF">His machine can work and it's probably
the best chance that we've got.</font>

744
00:56:26,467 --> 00:56:28,233
<font color="#FFFFFF">God, it's beyond belief.</font>

745
00:56:28,885 --> 00:56:32,237
<font color="#FFFFFF">If you fire them,
you'll have to fire me, too.</font>

746
00:56:32,847 --> 00:56:34,447
<font color="#FFFFFF">And me.</font>

747
00:56:34,641 --> 00:56:37,326
<font color="#FFFFFF">We're the best
cryptographic minds in Britain.</font>

748
00:56:37,978 --> 00:56:39,494
<font color="#FFFFFF">Are you going to fire us all?</font>

749
00:56:40,188 --> 00:56:42,914
<font color="#FFFFFF">Commander, at least
give us some more time.</font>

750
00:56:43,150 --> 00:56:46,637
<font color="#FFFFFF">Six months. And if the machine doesn't
produce any results that we need,</font>

751
00:56:46,737 --> 00:56:49,588
<font color="#FFFFFF">then we'll go back to doing things
the old way. How about that?</font>

752
00:56:56,579 --> 00:56:58,097
<font color="#FFFFFF">One month.</font>

753
00:56:58,331 --> 00:57:01,309
<font color="#FFFFFF">And then so help me God,
you're all gone.</font>

754
00:57:02,335 --> 00:57:03,978
<font color="#FFFFFF">Oh, leave him.</font>

755
00:57:11,929 --> 00:57:15,197
<font color="#FFFFFF">- Thank you.
- You're welcome.</font>

756
00:57:16,682 --> 00:57:19,034
<font color="#FFFFFF">Oh, and, Alan, your machine,</font>

757
00:57:22,106 --> 00:57:23,706
<font color="#FFFFFF">it had better bloody work.</font>

758
00:57:31,030 --> 00:57:33,215
<font color="#FFFFFF">Hugh...</font>

759
00:57:34,076 --> 00:57:35,635
<font color="#FFFFFF">I swear,</font>

760
00:57:36,619 --> 00:57:38,304
<font color="#FFFFFF">I'm not a spy.</font>

761
00:57:39,914 --> 00:57:42,034
<font color="#FFFFFF">Oh, for God's sake,
of course you're not a bloody spy.</font>

762
00:57:42,708 --> 00:57:45,528
<font color="#FFFFFF">- What?
- Denniston gave me the Beale cipher</font>

763
00:57:45,628 --> 00:57:48,146
<font color="#FFFFFF">and guess what? I cracked it.</font>

764
00:57:48,882 --> 00:57:52,036
<font color="#FFFFFF">"Ask, and it shall be given to you;
seek and ye shall find."</font>

765
00:57:52,135 --> 00:57:54,152
<font color="#FFFFFF">Matthew 7:7.
That was the key.</font>

766
00:57:55,806 --> 00:57:58,157
<font color="#FFFFFF">Far too simple for
the likes of you.</font>

767
00:57:59,976 --> 00:58:01,911
<font color="#FFFFFF">Pity Denniston disagrees.</font>

768
00:58:12,447 --> 00:58:14,005
<font color="#FFFFFF">Come in.</font>

769
00:58:16,577 --> 00:58:18,844
<font color="#FFFFFF">Sir, I think I've got Turing.</font>

770
00:58:19,788 --> 00:58:23,724
<font color="#FFFFFF">I tailed him to a pub last night where
he met a bloke. Exchanged an envelope.</font>

771
00:58:24,418 --> 00:58:27,853
<font color="#FFFFFF">So I follow this other fella,
pick him up, gave him a good shake.</font>

772
00:58:29,338 --> 00:58:32,858
<font color="#FFFFFF">- He's a poofter. He confessed.
- What?</font>

773
00:58:33,594 --> 00:58:35,996
<font color="#FFFFFF">The man admitted it.
Arnold Murray.</font>

